<subSubSection box="[199,1028,837,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,402,1042]" box="[199,1028,837,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,837,862]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name refers to the spicules on the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,402,1042]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,873,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is similar to several species, all predominantly black with the apical area of the forewing paler and with a relatively slender body (see under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[885,1004,910,933]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis box="[885,899,910,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[919,1004,910,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[1300,1436,909,934]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculata">
<emphasis box="[1300,1436,909,934]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. spiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[366,472,945,970]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumida">
<emphasis box="[366,472,945,970]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. tumida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In both species the aedeagus has a well developed dorsal apodeme and the shaft curved dorsally. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[374,507,981,1006]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculata">
<emphasis box="[374,507,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. spiculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the shaft of the aedeagus has spicules on the lateral margin that are absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">P. tumida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
